<br>
Thanks <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/umomur.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Momur</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Contributing Member</span><br>  Posts: 174<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/8/02 1:02:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1820.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Sounblaster Live/Win2K problems</span><hr size=1> I don't know if there is a way to assign IRQ's in Win2K. &amp; I don't know if your bios allows for assignment of IRQ's (which is a pain). Assuming not, move the card to a different slot:<br>
a) Pull the card<br>
b) boot<br>
c) shut down<br>
d) plug card into a new slot<br>
e) boot<br>
f) check your Modem, Video and Sound card IRQ's<br>
g) if good, begin play | if not go to (a) and repeat.<br>
<br>
Windows is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> supposed</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to have no problems sharing IRQ's and is supposedly <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> designed</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to operate with IRQ's shared, but I hear of plenty of problems like this. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/uphourtwomp.showPublicProfile?language=EN>PhourTwomp</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://youaveragepimp.homestead.com/files/spiral.GIF" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Contributing Member</span><br>  Posts: 291<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/8/02 1:58:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1820.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://sportsmed.starwave.com/i/nfl/clubhouse/nwe.gif width=63 height=63></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Sounblaster Live/Win2K problems</span><hr size=1> Yeah, I've had problems with my sblive on win2k, but I turned off sound at like lvl 20.  I got all sorts of delays and what not with sound and didn't feel like devoting time to remedy it /shrug <p><EMBED SRC="http://youaveragepimp.homestead.com/files/shwasig.swf" QUALITY=high BGCOLOR=#000000 WIDTH="400" HEIGHT="100" TYPE="application/x-shockwave-flash" PLUGINSPAGE="http://www.macromedia.com/shockwave/download/index.cgi?P1_Prod_Version=ShockwaveFlash"></EMBED> <a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=15088> Profile la~</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/usaxmoore.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Saxmoore</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 15<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/8/02 10:19:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1820.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Sounblaster Live/Win2K problems</span><hr size=1> I spent an entire weekend trying to fix W2K and SBLive sound problems.  Microsoft's ACPI decides to &quot;help&quot; you by sharing the IRQ's of various devices, and I'm pretty sure there's no way of changing those in Windows.<br>
You can check your BIOS, and see if you can specify settings for ACPI, mine couldn't.   I uninstalled ACPI, and it did change some of the devices around, but many were still sharing something.  (I use Norton Ghost, so it was easy to create an image before strting, and after each big change I was experimenting with).<br>
To make a long story short, there were no marked improvements with any of the changes I made.  I ended up going back to win98se.<br>
I have it on good authority that many of the sound problems are due to the fact that EQ is just too darn memory intensive (read: using too much sound processor), and that is where the problems stem from.  An upgraded sound card MAY help in that the processors are a little faster, but that probably won't completely fix the problems.<br>
Turning reverb off (for the echo problems, /reverb off), and turning down hardware acceleration in &quot;Sound and Multimedia properties&quot; (accessed from control panel) helped some more.  On the audio tab click advanced under sound playback, then preformance tab, and move the slider down a notch or two.<br>
It's not perfect, but it helps.  <br>
<br>
Wish i had better news for you <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   There is also a debug version of of the DX 8 .dll that allows you to turn OFF sound debugging, because Microsoft apparently shipped with it turned on.  I don't have it onhand, atm, but if you search through the EQ tech support site, you should be able to find this mentioned.<br>
